  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_226492044" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/226492044" />
    <a title="Netts" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5439497-netts"><img alt="Netts" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1327204722p2/5439497.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/226492044?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Netts" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Netts" href="/user/show/5439497-netts">Netts</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780805060126" href="/book/show/2050213.The_Appointment">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer226492044" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1316916182269838268">The fact that I grew up in communist Romania has a lot to do with how much I disliked this book. I don&apos;t think I would have loved the stilted style in any case, because I generally tend to find internal monologue narratives irritating. It&apos;s pretty hard to get that kind of voice to sound both plausible and engaging. But she won the Nobel Prize so I was cautiously optimistic, even though the year was 2009 and Obama got one just for showing up. (As an aside, the Swedish Academy rejected the likes o</span>
  <span id="freeText1316916182269838268" style="display:none">The fact that I grew up in communist Romania has a lot to do with how much I disliked this book. I don't think I would have loved the stilted style in any case, because I generally tend to find internal monologue narratives irritating. It's pretty hard to get that kind of voice to sound both plausible and engaging. But she won the Nobel Prize so I was cautiously optimistic, even though the year was 2009 and Obama got one just for showing up. (As an aside, the Swedish Academy rejected the likes of Tolstoy, Nabokov and Mark Twain so their judgement has always been pretty questionable.) The thing that truly bothered me about this is how it's billed as a work illustrative of life under Ceausescu's regime. It is bleak and oppressive and leaves one feeling isolated and confused so in that sense it could be said that it is a reflection on those years. But Kafka did that kind of thing long before and better and without political pretensions. Several Eastern Block writers have done so too with a dark sense of absurd humor that is much more authentic, at least to my experience (Andrey Kurkov springs to mind). I discussed this book with a Romanian friend who quipped that it was a humorless German view of the tragicomedy of Romanian life in the communist years. I can't express it any better than that. In the end what rang most false are the mundane but incongruous details: the descriptions of streets and shops and daily routines. They seemed expressionist and artificial rather than testimonial (Ex. Where were these dive bars that were open at all hours of the day? Just one of the details that would sound believable if you had lived elsewhere but completely imaginary to Romanians who lived through communism. And once you start to mess with reality for effect, it gets a lot harder to trust the veracity of everything else. You can bear witness or you can warp reality to provide poetic reflection but if you do both at once neither is going to ring true.) I wouldn't have minded so much if this had not been billed (in the synopsis and in every review though notably not in the book itself) as bearing witness to a time and place with which I was personally familiar. I can see how this book could be touching and profound but, caught in the web of its own pretentious artifice, it fails to reflect a real time and place, which would have been far more interesting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1316916182269838268" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

